<chapter xml:id="intro-groups">
  <title>Groups</title>

  <section xml:id="group-first-definitions">
    <title>First Definitions </title>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-grps">
      <title>Groups</title>


      <definition xml:id="def-binop">
        <title>Binary Operation</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <em>binary operation</em> on a set <m>S</m> is a function
            <me>
              -\cdot-:S\times S\to S,\text{given by } (x,y)\to x\cdot y.
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <remark>
        We often write <m>xy</m> instead of <m>x\cdot y</m> for simplicity.
      </remark>

      <definition xml:id="def-group">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <em>group</em> is a pair <m>(G, \cdot)</m> where <m>G</m> is a set and <m>\cdot</m> is a <xref text="title" ref="def-binop"/> on <m>G</m>, called <em>group multiplication</em>, satisfying the following properties:
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  (Associativity) for all <m>x,y,z\in G</m> we have <m>(x\cdot y)\cdot z=x\cdot (y\cdot z)</m> 
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  (Identity Element) there exists <m>e\in G</m> such that <m>e·x=x·e=x</m> for all <m>x\in G</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  (Inverses) for each <m>x\in G</m>, there is an element <m>y\in G</m> such that <m>xy=e=yx</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <remark>
        Although a group is a pair, we will usually refer to the group by only naming the underlying set, <m>G</m>.
      </remark>

      <remark>
        We say that <q><m>S</m> is closed under the operation <m>\cdot</m></q>, when we want to emphasize that for any <m>x,y\in S</m> the result of the operation, <m>xy</m>, is an element of <m>S</m>. However note that closure is really part of the definition of a binary operation on a set, and it is implicitly assumed whenever we consider such an operation.
      </remark>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-unique-identity">
        <statement>
          <p>
            In a group <m>G</m>, the element <m>e</m> satisfying the second axiom of <xref ref="def-group" /> is unique, and we thus refer to it as the <em>identity element</em> of <m>G</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            If <m>ex = x = xe</m> and <m>e'x = x = xe'</m> for all <m>x</m>, then <m>e = ee' = e'</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-unique-inverse">
        <statement>
          <p>
            In a group <m>G</m>, for each <m>x</m>, the element <m>y</m> satisfying the last axiom of <xref ref="def-group" /> is unique.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Proof. For a given <m>x</m>, if <m>yx = xy = e</m> and <m>zx = xz = e</m> fo some <m>y</m> and <m>z</m>, then <m>z = ez = (yx)z = y(xz) = ye = y</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>

      <remark>
        We will call the element <m>y</m> satisfying the last axiom of <xref ref="def-group" /> <em>the inverse</em> of <m>x</m> and we will henceforth denote it by <m>x^{-1}</m>.
      </remark>  

      <definition xml:id="def-abelian">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A group <m>G</m> is an <em>abelian group</em> if <m>\cdot</m> is commutative; i.e., <m>x \cdot y = y \cdot x</m> for all <m>x,y \in G</m>. Often, but not always, the group operation for an abelian group is written as <m>+</m> instead of <m>\cdot</m>. In this case the inverse of an element <m>x</m> is written <m>-x</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <problem xml:id="order-4-abelian">
        <p>
          Every group of order <m>4</m> is abelian.
        </p>

        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>G</m> be a group with <m>4</m> elements, and suppose there are elements <m>a,b\in G</m> such that <m>ab\neq ba</m> for some elements <m>a, b\in G</m>. Since <m>ab \neq ba</m>, we must have <m>a \neq b</m>, <m>a \neq e</m>, and <m>b\neq e</m>. Since <m>G</m> has only <m>4</m> elements and <m>ab \neq ba</m>, either <m>ab \in \{e, a, b\}</m> or <m>ba \in\{e, a, b\}</m>. Without loss, say the former occurs. But <m>ab = e</m> implies <m>b=a\inv</m> and we know <m>a\inv</m> commutes with <m>a</m>, and hence this is not possible. If <m>ab = a</m>, then <m>b = e</m> and if <m>ab = b</m> then <m>a = 1</m>, both of which are impossible. Since a, b were arbitrary, G must be abelian.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </problem>
      
      <lemma xml:id="lem-group-props">
        <title>Properties of Groups</title>
        
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>G</m> is a group and <m>x,y,z, a_1,\ldots,a_n \in G</m>, then:
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  if <m>xy = xz</m>, then <m>y=z</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
      
              <li>
                <p>
                  if <m>yx = zx</m>, then <m>y = z</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
      
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(x^{-1})^{-1} = x</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
      
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(a_1 \dots a_n)^{-1} = a_n^{-1} \dots a_1^{-1}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
      
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(x^{-1}yx)^n = x^{-1}y^nx</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>          

      <proposition xml:id="prop-gpex">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The <term>trivial subgroup</term> is the group with a single element <m>\{e\}</m>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  For any set <m>S</m>, the permutations on <m>S</m> <me>\rm{Perm}(S)=\{f:S\to S \ | \ f \text{ is a bijection}\}</me> form a non-abelian group under composition.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  For any field <m>F</m> and positive integer <m>n</m>, let 
                  <me>
                    \operatorname{GL}_n(F)=\{ \text{invertible }  n \times n \text{ matrices with entries in } F\}.
                  </me> 
                  By invertible I mean those matrices that have two-sided inverses, but in turns out that if an <m>n \times n</m> matrix has a left inverse then it it is automatically a right inverse too, and vice versa. Then <m>\operatorname{GL}_n(F)</m> is a non-abelian group under matrix multiplication.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  For any <m>n</m>, let <m>\mathbb{Z}/(n)</m> denote the integers modulo <m>n</m>. Then <m>(\mathbb{Z}/(n), +)</m> is an abelian group where <m>+</m> denotes addition modulo <m>n</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  For any field <m>F</m> (e.g., <m>\mathbb{Q}</m>, <m>{\mathbb{R}}</m>, <m>\mathbb{C}</m> or <m>\mathbb{Z}/p</m> for a prime <m>p</m>), the set <m>F^\times := F \setminus \{0\}</m> is an abelian group under the usual multiplication.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

