        </solution>
      </problem>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-dirprop-gp">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Direct products of groups are groups
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-d2n">
      <title>Dihedral Groups</title>
      
      <p>
        We now discuss the important example of dihedral groups in detail.
      </p>


      <definition xml:id="def-iso-and-sym">
        <statement>
          <p>
            For any integer <m>n \geq 3</m>, let <m>P_n</m> denote a regular <m>n</m>-gon.

            An <em>isometry</em> of the plane is a function <m>f: {\mathbb{R}}^2 \to {\mathbb{R}}^2</m> that is a bijection and preserves the Euclideal distance <m>(d(f(A),f(B))=d(A,B)</m> for any <m>A,B\in {\mathbb{R}}^2</m>).

            A <em>symmetry</em> of <m>P_n</m> is an isometry that maps <m>P_n</m> to itself.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <remark>
        By the latter I don't mean that <m>f</m> fixes each of the points of <m>P_n</m>, but rather that <m>f(P_n) = P_n</m>, that is every point of <m>P_n</m> is mapped to a (possibly different) point of <m>P_n</m> and every point of <m>P_n</m> is the image of some point in <m>P_n</m> via <m>f</m>. It is clear that the composition of two symmetries of <m>P_n</m> is again a symmetry of <m>P_n</m>, so that composition is a binary operation on <m>D_n</m>.
      </remark>

      <definition xml:id="def-d2n">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <em>dihedral group</em> <m>D_{2n}</m> is the set of symmetries of the regular <m>n</m>-gon <m>P_n</m> equipped with the binary operation given by composition. 
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Prove that the dihedral group <m>D_{2n}</m> is indeed a group.
        </p>
      </problem>

    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-symmetric">
      <title>Symmetric Groups</title>

      <p>
        Let's introduce another very important example: symmetric groups.
      </p>

      <definition xml:id="def-permutation">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <em>permutation</em> of a set <m>X</m> is a bijective function <m>\sigma:X\to X</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <definition xml:id="def-perm-group">
        <statement>
          <p>
            For any <m>n\in\N</m>, the <em>symmetric group</em> is the set <m>S_n</m> of all permutations of the set <m>\{1,\dots,n\}</m> equipped with the composition of functions as its binary operation.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <remark>
        For any finite set <m>|X|=n</m>, we may think of <m>S_n</m> as the <em>permutation group</em> of <m>X</m>, which is sometimes written <m>\operatorname{Perm}(X)</m>.
      </remark>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>S_n</m> is indeed a group for all <m>n\in\N</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <p>
        We can write an element <m>\sigma</m> of <m>S_n</m> as a table of values: 
        <me>
          \begin{pmatrix} 
            1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 &amp; \cdots &amp; n \\
            \sigma(1) &amp; \sigma(2) &amp; \sigma(3) &amp; \cdots &amp; \sigma(n)
          \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
      </p>


      <definition xml:id="def-cycle">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>i_1, \dots, i_m</m> are distinct integers between <m>1</m> and <m>n</m>, then <m>\sigma=(i_1 \, i_2 \, \dots i_m)</m> denotes the element of <m>S_n</m> that satisfies <me>\sigma(i_1)=i_2, \sigma(i_2)=i_3, \dots, \sigma(i_{m-1})=i_m, \sigma(i_m)=i_1 \text{ and } \sigma(k)=k \text{ for } k\in[n] \setminus \{i_1, \dots, i_m\}.</me> Such a permutation is called a <em>cycle</em> or an <m>m</m><em>-cycle</em> if we want to emphasize its length. A <m>2</m>-cycle is often called a <em>transposition</em>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      
      <problem>
        <p>
          Determine the number of <m>1</m>-cycles in <m>S_n</m>. 
        </p>
      </problem>

      <remark>
        Note that distinct lists of integers represent the same cycle if they are cyclical rearrangements of each other, e.g., <m>(1 \, 2 \, 3) = (2 \, 3 \, 1)</m>. However, <m>(1 \, 2 \, 3) \neq (2 \, 1 \, 3)</m>.
      </remark>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Disjoint cycles commute, that is, if <m>i_1 , i_2 \, \dots i_m, j_1 , j_2 \, \dots j_k\in [n]</m>, <me>\sigma_1=(i_1 \, i_2 \, \dots i_m), \quad \sigma_2=(j_1 \, j_2 \, \dots j_k)</me> and <me>\{i_1 , i_2 , \dots i_m\}\cap \{j_1 , j_2 , \dots j_k\}=\emptyset</me> then <m>\sigma_1 \circ \sigma_2=\sigma_2\circ \sigma_1</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-cycledecomp">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Each <m>\sigma\in S_n</m> can be written as a product (composition) of disjoint cycles, and such a factorization is unique up to the ordering of the factors.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Each <m>\sigma\in S_n</m> can be written a product of transpositions; i.e., <m>S_n</m> is generated by transpositions.                  
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <remark>
        For the uniqueness part of statement (1) in the above proposition one needs to establish a convention regarding 1-cycles, that is one needs to stipulate either that the 1-cycles will not be recorded (which gives the shortest such factorization) or that all the 1-cycles will be recorded (which gives the longest such factorization, but also the only one that makes it clear what the number <m>n</m> is).
      </remark>

    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-quat">
      <title>The Quaternions</title>

      <p>
        For our last example we mention the group of <em>quaternions</em>, written <m>Q_8</m>.
      </p>
      
      <definition xml:id="def-quaternions">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The quaternion group <m>Q_8</m> is a group with <m>8</m> elements <me>Q_8=\{ 1, -1, i, -i, j, -j, k, -k \}</me> satisfying the following relations: <m>1</m> is the identity element and <me>i^2 = -1, j^2 = -1, k^2 =-1, ij = k, jk = i, ki = j,</me> <me>(-1)i = -i, (-1)j = -j, (-1)k = -k, (-1)(-1) = 1.</me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Verify that <m>Q_8</m> is a group. Provide a specific example to show that <m>Q_8</m> is not an abelian group.
        </p>
      </problem>
    </subsection> 

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-order">
      <title>Order</title>
      
      <definition xml:id="def-element-order">
        <statement>
          <p>
            In a group <m>G</m>, the <em>order of an element</em> <m>x</m> is the least positive integer <m>n</m> such that <m>x^n = e</m>. If no such <m>n</m> exists, we say <m>x</m> has infinite order. We write <m>|x|</m> for the order of <m>x</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <definition xml:id="def-order-group">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <em>order of a group</em> <m>G</m> is the cardinality of the set <m>G</m>, denoted <m>|G|</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <problem>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that any group of order <m>4</m> is abelian.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            
          </p>
        </solution>
      </problem>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-orderelgp">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>G</m> be a group and <m>x \in G</m> any element. 
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Prove that if <m>|x| = n</m>, then <m>e, x, \dots, x^{n-1}</m> are all distinct elements of <m>G</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                    
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Prove that if <m>|x| = \infty</m>, then <m>x^i \ne x^j</m> for all integers (positive or negative) <m>,j</m> with <m>i \ne j</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Conclude <m>|x| \leq |G|</m> in all cases.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Prove <m>|S_n|=n!</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Prove that the order of a permutation is the least common multiple of the lengths of the cycles it is a product of.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>G, H</m> be groups and let <m>x, y</m> be elements of <m>G</m>. 
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>|x|=\left|\{x^n \ | n\in \Z \}\right|</m> and in particular <m>|x| \leq |G|</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
                
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove or disprove: if <m>x,y</m> have finite order then <m>xy</m> has finite order. 
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>G</m> be a group. 
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>g \in G</m> be an element of finite order. Show that <m>g^m</m> has finite order for any integer <m>m \geq 0</m>, and in fact <me> |g^m| = \frac{\lcm(m,|g|)}{m} = \frac{|g|}{\gcd(m, |g|))}.</me> 
              </p>
            </li>
                
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that for all <m>g, h</m> in <m>G</m>, <m>|gh| = |hg|</m> holds.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </problem>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-d2n-order">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Every element in <m>D_{2n}</m> can be written as <m>r^j</m> or <m>r^js</m> for <m>0 \leq j \leq n-1</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>|D_{2n}|=2n</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <lemma xml:id="lem-group-element-order">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>x^m = e</m> then <m>|x| \mid m</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </lemma>


    </subsection>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-gen-cyclic-gp">
    <title>Generators and Cyclic Groups</title>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-gp-generators">
      <title>Generators</title>
      
    <definition xml:id="def-groupgenerate">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A subset <m>S</m> of a group <m>G</m> is said to <em>generate</em> <m>G</m> if every element of <m>G</m> is equal to a product of elements of <m>S</m> and their inverses (with repetitions allowed). 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Assume that the regular <m>n</m>-gon <m>P_n</m> is drawn in the plane with its center at the origin and one vertex on the <m>x</m> axis. If <m>r</m> denotes rotation about the origin by <m>\frac{2\pi}{n}</m> radians counter-clockwise, then <m>r \in D_{2n}</m>. It’s inverse is rotation by <m>2 \pi/n</m> clock-wise. For another example, for any line of symmetry of <m>P_n</m>, reflection about that line gives an element of <m>D_{2n}</m>. By our convention for how to draw <m>P_n</m>, the <m>x</m>-axis is a line of symmetry for <m>P_n</m>, and we let <m>s</m> denote reflection about the <m>x</m>-axis.
    </p>

    <problem>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove <m>|r|=n</m> and <m>|s|=2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that <m>sr</m> is a reflection and hence that <m>srsr=1_{{\mathbb{R}}^2}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>

    <problem>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that <m>D_{2n}</m> is generated by <m>r</m> and any reflection. 
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that if <m>p\ge 3</m> is prime then <m>D_{2p}</m> is generated by any two distinct reflections.               
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>

    <problem>
      <p>
        For <m>n\ge 2</m> prove that <m>S_n</m> is generated by <m>(12)</m> and the <m>n</m>-cycle <m>(12\cdots n)</m>.
      </p>
    </problem>
    
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-cyclic-gp">
      <title>Cyclic Groups</title>
      
      <definition xml:id="def-cyclic-group">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>G</m> is a generated by a single element, i.e. <m>G   = \langle x \rangle</m> for some <m>x \in G</m>, then <m>G</m> is called a <em>cyclic group</em>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>G=\langle x\rangle</m> be a cyclic group. Then <m>G=\langle x^{-1}\rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove <m>(\mathbb{Z},+)</m> is generated by <m>1</m> or <m>-1</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Prove <m>(\mathbb{Z}/(n),+)</m> is generated by <m>[a]_n</m> for any integer <m>a</m> such that <m>\operatorname{gcd}(a,n)=1</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>(\mathbb Q, +)</m> is not a cyclic group.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-cyclicabelian">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that any cyclic group is abelian.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>\operatorname{GL}_2(\mathbb Z/(2))</m> is not cyclic.
        </p>
      </problem>

    </subsection>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-subgroups">
    <title>Subgroups</title>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-subgrp-defn-ex">
      <title>Definition and Examples</title>

      <definition xml:id="def-subgroup">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A nonempty subset <m>H</m> of a group <m>G</m> is called a <em>subgroup</em> provided <m>H</m> is a group under the multiplication law of <m>G</m>. The fact that <m>H</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m> is denoted <m>H\leq G</m> or <m>H&lt;G</m> if we also mean that <m>H\neq G</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <lemma xml:id="lem-subgrouptest">
        <title>Subgroup Tests</title>
        
        
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If a subset <m>H</m> of a group <m>G</m> is nonempty and closed under multiplication and inversion, then <m>H</m> is a subgroup.
                </p>
              </li>
    
              <li>
                <p>
                  If a subset <m>H</m> of a group <m>G</m> is nonempty and satisfies for all <m>x,y \in H</m>, <m>xy^{-1} \in H</m>, then <m>H</m> is a subgroup.
                </p>
              </li>
    
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </lemma>

      <example>
        <p>
          Prove the following:
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\{e_G\}</m> and <m>G</m> are the <em>trivial subgroups</em> of <m>G</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\Z\leq\Q\leq\R\leq\C</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\Z^\times\leq\Q^\times\leq\R^\times\leq\C^\times</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>n\in\N</m> and define <m>n\Z=\{x\in\Z|x=nk\;\text{for some}\;k\in\Z\}</m>. Prove <m>n\Z\leq\Z</m> for all <m>n</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a group. For any <m>g\in G</m>, prove that the set <m>Z_G(g)=\{x\in G|gx=xg\}</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </example>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-subgroup-properties">
        <title>Properties of Subgroups</title>
        
        
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>H</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m> and <m>K</m> is a subgroup of <m>H</m>, then <m>K</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>H_\alpha</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m> for all <m>\alpha</m> in an index set <m>J</m>, then <m>H=\bigcap_{\alpha\in J} H_\alpha</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Let <m>G</m> be a group and <m>H</m>, <m>H'</m> subgroups. Prove that <m>H\cup H'</m> is a subgroup if and only if <m>H\subseteq H'</m> or <m>H'\subseteq H</m>.

                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>


      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>H</m> be a subgroup of <m>G</m> and fix some element <m>g\in G</m>. Prove that <m>gHg^{-1}=\{ghg^{-1} \mid h\in H\}</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m> of the same order as <m>H</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <definition xml:id="def-altgroup">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <em>alternating group</em> <m>A_n</m> is the subset of all even cycles of <m>S_n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>A_n</m> is a subgroup of <m>S_n</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <definition xml:id="def-slg">
        <statement>
          <p>
            For any field <m>F</m>, the <em>special linear group</em>
            <me>
              \SL_n(F)=\{A \mid A = n\times n \;\text{matrix with entries in}\; F, \det(A)=1_F\}
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>SL_n(F)</m> is a subgroup of <m>GL_n(F)</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>
      
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-center">
      <title>The Center of a Group</title>

      <definition xml:id="def-gpcenter">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <em>center</em> of a group <m>G</m> often written <m>Z(G)</m>, is the set of elements of <m>G</m> that commute with every element of <m>G</m>. That is, 
            <me>
              Z(G)=\{x \in G \, | \, xy = yx\,\text{ for all $y \in G$}\}.
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>Z(G)</m> is an abelian subgroup for any group <m>G</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>
      

      <problem>
        <p>
          Find <m>Z(D_{2n})</m> for <m>n \geq 3</m>. Your answer will depend on whether <m>n</m> is even or odd.
        </p>
      </problem>


    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-gensubgp">
      <title>Generated Subgroups</title>


      <definition xml:id="def-gensubgp">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given a group <m>G</m> and a subset <m>X</m> of <m>G</m>, the <em>subgroup of <m>G</m> generated by <m>X</m></em> is <me>\langle X \rangle := \bigcap_{H \leq G, H \supseteq X} H.</me> If <m>X=\{x\}</m> is a set with one element then we write <m>\langle X \rangle=\langle x \rangle</m> and we refer to this as the <em>cyclic subgroup generated by</em> <m>x</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>


      <lemma xml:id="lem-gensubgp">
        <statement>
          <p>
            For a subset <m>X</m> of <m>G</m>, the elements of <m>\langle X \rangle</m> can be described as: <me>\langle X \rangle = \left\{x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m} \mid m \geq 0, j_1, \dots, j_m \in \mathbb{Z}\text{ and }x_1, \dots, x_m \in X \right\}.</me>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>S= \left\{x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m} \mid m \geq 0, j_1, \dots, j_m \in \mathbb{Z}\text{ and }x_1, \dots, x_m \in X \right\}</m>. Since <m>\langle X \rangle</m> is a subgroup that contains <m>X</m>, it is closed under products and inverses, and thus must contain all elements of <m>S</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            For the opposite containment, we just need to show the set <m>S</m> really is a subgroup. We use the one step test:
          </p>
  
          <p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>S \ne \emptyset</m> since we allow <m>m = 0</m> and declare the empty product to be <m>e_G</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
  
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m}</m> and <m>y_1^{i_1} \cdots y_n^{i_m}</m> are in <m>S</m> then 
                  <me>
                    x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m}(y_1^{i_1} \cdots y_n^{i_m})^{-1}=x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m} y_n^{-i_m} \cdots y_1^{-i_1}
                  </me> 
                  is also in <m>S</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
    
            <p>
              Therefore <m>S\leq G</m> and <m>X\subseteq S</m> (by taking <m>m=1</m> and <m>j_1=1</m>) and by the minimality of <m>\langle X \rangle</m> we obtain <m>\langle X \rangle\subseteq S</m>.
            </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>

      <problem>
        <p>
          <xref ref="lem-gensubgp"/> implies that for an element <m>x</m> of a group <m>G</m>, <m>\langle x\rangle=\{x^j \mid j\in \mathbb{Z}\}</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Verify <m>D_{2n}=\langle r,s \rangle</m>, meaning that <m>D_{2n}</m> is the subgroup of <m>D_{2n}</m> generated by <m>\{r,s\}</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>A_n</m> is the subgroup of <m>S_n</m> generated by all produts of <m>2</m>-cyclies (disjoint or not). In symbols, 
          <me>
            A_n=\langle (i \ j )(k \ l) \mid i,j,k,l \in \{1, \ldots, n\}\rangle.
          </me>
          
        </p>
      </problem>


      <problem>
        <p>
          Consider the set <m>\mu=\{z\in \C \setminus \{0\} \mid z^n = 1 \text{ for some integer }n \geq 1\}</m>, which is a subgroup of <m>( \C \setminus \{0\} , \cdot)</m> (a fact you need not prove).
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that for each integer <m>m \geq 1</m>, there is a unique subgroup <m>H_m\leq \mu</m> with <m>|H_m|=m</m> and that <m>H_m</m> is cyclic. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that every finitely generated subgroup of <m>\mu</m> has finitely many elements. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>\mu</m> is not finitely generated.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </problem>

    </subsection>

